In article <1992Oct29.174332.1601@guvax.acc.georgetown.edu> denning@guvax.acc.georgetown.edu writes:
>The arguments against registration seem to fall into two classes:
>1) it's futile and 2) we shouldn't trust the government.

You then go on to explain why we should in fact trust the government.
Do you have any comments on the first objection -- that it wouldn't
work?

Incidentally, these are not the only two classes.  There is, for
example, the claim that the Constitution does not authorize the
government to mandate key registration.

>Dorothy Denning

